05436nam a22006615i 9780226716831DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021016881  a97802267168317 a10.7208/chicago/97802267168312doi  a(DE-B1597)602124  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aE185.97.N47bA3 2021 4aE185.97.N47bA3 2021eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a323.0922231 aNesbitt, George B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeing Somebody and Black Besides :bAn Untold Memoir of Midcentury Black Life /cGeorge B. Nesbitt; ed. by Prexy Nesbitt, Zeb Larson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tForeword -- tA Note on St. Clair Drake’s “Foreword” -- tForeword to the George Nesbitt Manuscript -- tA Note on the Manuscript -- tPreface -- t1. Our Family’s Great Migration -- t2. A Family Which Stayed Together -- t3. Learning to Be Somebody -- t4. The Comfort of My Negroness -- t5. Going to University -- t6. Town and Gown -- t7. Lawyer by Day, Redcap at Night -- t8. The Army and Its Apartheid -- t9. The Ugly Specter of Race Discrimination -- t10. Poking at the Good, White Liberals -- t11. An Exceptional Family in the Lawndale Ghetto -- t12. The Future of Our People -- tPostscript -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn immersive multigenerational memoir that recounts the hopes, injustices, and triumphs of a Black family fighting for access to the American dream in the twentieth century. The late Chicagoan George Nesbitt could perhaps best be described as an ordinary man with an extraordinary gift for storytelling. In his newly uncovered memoir—written fifty years ago, yet never published—he chronicles in vivid and captivating detail the story of how his upwardly mobile Midwestern Black family lived through the tumultuous twentieth century. Spanning three generations, Nesbitt’s tale starts in 1906 with the Great Migration and ends with the Freedom Struggle in the 1960s. He describes his parents’ journey out of the South, his struggle against racist military authorities in World War II, the promise and peril of Cold War America, the educational and professional accomplishments he strove for and achieved, the lost faith in integration, and, despite every hardship, the unwavering commitment by three generations of Black Americans to fight for a better world. Through all of it—with his sharp insights, nuance, and often humor—we see a family striving to lift themselves up in a country that is working to hold them down. Nesbitt’s memoir includes two insightful forewords: one by John Gibbs St. Clair Drake (1911–90), a pioneer in the study of African American life, the other a contemporary rumination by noted Black studies scholar Imani Perry. A rare first-person, long-form narrative about Black life in the twentieth century, Being Somebody and Black Besides is a remarkable literary-historical time capsule that will delight modern readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican American lawyersvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszIllinoisvBiography. 0aCivil rights workerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aRace discriminationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  amemoir, chicago, midwest, great, migration, freedom, struggle, 1960s, racism, african, american, history, integration, twentieth, century.1 aDrake, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrake, St. Clair,